   {:e #blake3 "a08b9f2033154826a62f997caa57c14a46842b83926b79a3356e237433c50d0e" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-ceb5b13b; CACHE ARCHITECTURE AUDIT (Session 039): Found 5 independent caching layers with 3 different invalidation strategies. (1) store.bin — bincode-serialized Store, invalidated by write_tx() via invalidate_cache() which DELETES the file, forcing 2.5s full rebuild from 7K+ EDN txn files on next load. (2) fitness.json — CachedValue<FitnessScore> with txn_fingerprint, NOT invalidated by invalidate_cache() — STALE BUG. (3) coherence.json — CachedValue<CoherenceReport> with txn_fingerprint, NOT invalidated — STALE BUG. (4) analytics.json — AnalyticsCache with count-based validation (weaker than fingerprint), NOT invalidated — STALE RISK. (5) MaterializedViews — in-memory only, updated incrementally during transact(), lost on process exit, correct within process lifetime. Root cause of UAQ-6 overhead: write_tx() deletes store.bin on every status call (presentation count tracking), forcing 2.5s rebuild. The fitness.json and coherence.json stale bugs are latent — fingerprint comparison usually catches them, but edge cases exist under concurrent writes.; Session entity: :recon/trace-7f076f475979d540; Session entity: :recon/trace-5f58b28cdd10d80d; Session entity: :recon/trace-e3e8d7e1e9672c98; Session entity: :task/t-3b7925a5; Session entity: :task/t-2af39922; Session entity: :task/t-02fe1d75; Session entity: :task/t-83506b53; Session entity: :recon/trace-32842ab4b49b3f31; FEGH-1 COMPLETE: generate_bridge_hypotheses implemented. Finds connected components in entity reference graph via union-find, scores bridges by log(community_size_product)/log(total) + project_delta gradient, surfaces top bridge as speculative context block in braid status. On 73K datom store: 2 communities detected, bridge question surfaced with alpha=0.0199. Labels use entity_label with truncation. Wired into build_status_projection as Speculative precedence block.; DAEMON-AS-LIVESTORE-EXTENSION (Session 039): The daemon is not a separate architecture — it's the same LiveStore with a longer lifetime. CLI mode: LiveStore::open() → run_command(&mut live) → live drops (store.bin already written). Daemon mode: LiveStore::open() → loop { socket.accept() → handle_request(&mut live) } → store.bin written on each mutation (crash recovery free). This means: (1) All command implementations work identically in CLI and daemon mode — they take &mut LiveStore, not DiskLayout + Store separately. (2) The daemon's Unix socket protocol is a thin RPC layer over the same command functions. (3) Performance: daemon avoids the 300ms LiveStore::open() on every command because the store stays in memory. Status drops from ~500ms to ~100ms (50ms coherence + 50ms routing). (4) Multi-agent: daemon detects external txn files by watching the txns/ directory (inotify/kqueue). On new external file, reads + applies incrementally. The LiveStore's in-memory state is always the superset of all known txn files. (5) W-alpha integration: the daemon's private working set is a second Store held alongside the shared store. Runtime observations go to W-alpha, not the shared store. (6) The 120+ load_store/write_tx call sites migrate to LiveStore methods, making the daemon a zero-marginal-cost extension rather than a rewrite.; Session entity: :task/t-8f387189; Session entity: :recon/trace-e4315cd2370efe9b; Session entity: :task/t-a4a22f27; Session entity: :recon/trace-80ae0948ca54c4de; LIVESTORE ARCHITECTURE PROPOSAL (Session 039): The fundamental insight: DiskLayout and Store are separate objects that don't know about each other. write_tx() is a filesystem operation with no concept of current store state — it writes a file and deletes the cache because that's the only safe thing a filesystem layer can do. The fix is not better cache invalidation but ELIMINATING THE SEPARATION between the store and its persistence layer. DESIGN: LiveStore struct owns both DiskLayout and Store. LiveStore::open(path) deserializes store.bin once (300ms). LiveStore::store() returns &Store (0ms). LiveStore::write_tx(&mut self, tx) does three things atomically: (1) write EDN txn file to disk for durability, (2) apply transaction to in-memory Store via transact(), (3) serialize updated Store to store.bin via write_index_cache. This makes the cache ALWAYS fresh because every write updates it. No invalidation, no rebuild, no stale data — by construction. WHAT DIES: invalidate_cache(), fitness.json, coherence.json, analytics.json, incremental rebuild path, slow rebuild path, fingerprint validation, meta.json. ~400 lines of cache management code becomes self.layout.write_index_cache(&self.store). WHAT THIS ENABLES: (1) The daemon (PERF-4) becomes trivial — a LiveStore that doesn't exit. CLI mode and daemon mode share the same LiveStore, same write-through semantics, same persistence guarantees. The only difference is process lifetime. (2) Sub-second braid status (~500ms: 300ms deserialize + 50ms coherence + 50ms routing + 100ms write-through). (3) Correct-by-construction caching — impossible to serve stale data. CRASH SAFETY: The append-only guarantee (C1) makes this bulletproof. If the process crashes between 'update in-memory' and 'write store.bin', the txn file is already on disk — the next LiveStore::open() picks it up via the incremental path. No data loss, no corruption, no inconsistency. PERFORMANCE MODEL: LiveStore::open() 300ms (bincode, once per process). live.store() 0ms (pointer deref). live.write_tx() ~100ms (txn file + bincode serialize). Total braid status: ~500ms. From 97s to 0.5s = 194x improvement from start of session.; Session entity: :recon/trace-1ae83507ff889707; Session entity: :task/t-cb5f2fd4; Session entity: :recon/trace-c8fffba89b9190ab; DERIVED CACHE ELIMINATION (Session 039): With LiveStore write-through + the ISP O(n^2) fix from earlier this session, three of the five cache files become unnecessary: (1) fitness.json — store.fitness() is O(1) via MaterializedViews which are updated incrementally during transact(). The separate JSON cache was needed when fitness computation was expensive. Now it's 0.2ms. DELETE. (2) coherence.json — check_coherence_fast() was 48s before the ISP fix. Now it's 50ms. The JSON cache added complexity for 50ms savings. DELETE. (3) analytics.json — spectral decomposition is expensive but called rarely (braid status --deep only). Keep the --force flag, remove the cache — users who run --deep accept the cost. DELETE. What remains: store.bin (the LiveStore's persistence file) and the txn files (durable log). Two layers, not five. Zero invalidation strategies, not three.; Session entity: :task/t-e218963d; Session entity: :task/t-09433107" :op :assert}
